Quantifying the Loudness War¶

The Loudness War is the trend of increasing loudness levels in recorded music.

I tested this assumption as part of my project in the Visual Data Science of my Data Science Masters' at the Technical University of Vienna.

Below, I present a comprehensive report detailing my findings:

As a data source, I am using Yamac Eren Ay's Spotify Dataset 1921-2020, 600k+ Tracks dataset from kaggle. I used the older 160k tracks version dataset in the past. This version is not available anymore, so I updated it to the new version. The findings remain similar.

In [1]:
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

Read dataset from csv and clean it.¶

During this phase, I extract the 'year' from the 'release_date' column. It's important to note that the 'release_date' column has varying formats, either 'YYYY-MM-DD' or just 'YYYY'.

The loudness is measured in dB.

In [2]:
# load data from csv, selecting only 'release_date' and 'loudness' columns
df = pd.read_csv('data/tracks.csv', usecols=['release_date', 'loudness'])
In [3]:
# convert 'release_date' to datetime and extract year
df['year'] = pd.to_datetime(df['release_date'], errors='coerce').dt.year
In [4]:
# drop rows with missing 'year' or 'loudness' values
df.dropna(subset=['year', 'loudness'], inplace=True)
In [5]:
nr_of_years = df['year'].max() - df['year'].min() + 1

f, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 6), sharex=False)

sns.histplot(df["loudness"], ax=axes[1], kde=True)

The dataset has very few records before and around 1920. To determine the exact amount of data points, let's count the number of values in this range.

Starting at 1922, we have enough data for our investigation.

df.query('year >= 1922', inplace=True)

Next, I'll visualize the data using a scatterplot. Given the vast number of data points and the discrete nature of the 'year' column, I've added a random horizontal jitter within a range of +/- 0.5 to better discern the data density.

In [9]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))

# create new year column with added random jitter, for better scatterplot visualization
jitter = np.random.uniform(-0.5, 0.5, size=len(df))
df['year_jittered'] = df['year'] + jitter

sns.scatterplot(data=df, x='year_jittered', y='loudness', marker='.', alpha=.01)

plt.xlim(df['year_jittered'].min(), df['year_jittered'].max())

plt.title('Loudness over Years')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Loudness (dB)')

plt.show()

Statistical Analysis¶

In order to analyse the relationship between the year and loudness, I decided to use a spearman rank correlation coefficient. This test does not require a normally distributed dataset.

In [10]:
from scipy.stats import spearmanr

# compute Spearman rank correlation between 'year' and 'loudness'
coef, p_value = spearmanr(df['year'], df['loudness'])

print(f"Spearman rank correlation coefficient: {coef:.3f}")
print(f"P-value: {p_value}")

Spearman rank correlation coefficient: 0.496
P-value: 0.0

With a coefficient of ~0.5 and a p-value below the threshold of the scipy function, there is a clear positive correlation between the year and the loudness.

Fitting a Linear Model¶

In a next step I want to quantify the change per year by fitting a linear model and getting the slope.

In [11]:
import statsmodels.formula.api as smf

# Fit a linear regression model to predict 'loudness' based on 'year'

results = smf.ols('loudness ~ year', data=df).fit()

print(results.summary())

In [12]:
intercept = results.params['Intercept']
slope = results.params['year']

print(f"Slope of loudness over years: {slope:.4f}")

Slope of loudness over years: 0.0997

Result¶

The loudness of the tracks in this dataset increases by 0.1 dB per year.

To visualize this, I added the regression line to the scatterplot of before.

(Note that the blue dot in the legend does not exactly represent a data point in the visualization. An exact representation of this size and transparency would barely be visible.)

In [13]:
import matplotlib.lines as mlines

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))

sns.scatterplot(data=df, x='year_jittered', y='loudness', marker='.', alpha=.01, label='Tracks')

# plot regression line to visualize the trend in loudness over the years
year_start, year_end = df['year'].min(), df['year'].max()
plt.plot([year_start, year_end], [intercept + slope * year_start, intercept + slope * year_end], linewidth=2, color='red', label='Regression Line')

plt.xlim(df['year_jittered'].min(), df['year_jittered'].max())

plt.title('Loudness Trend over Years')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Loudness (dB)')

legend_handle = [mlines.Line2D([], [], color='blue', marker='.', linestyle='None', markersize=5, label='Tracks'),
                 mlines.Line2D([], [], color='red', linestyle='-', markersize=10, label='Regression Line')]
plt.legend(handles=legend_handle, loc='upper left')

plt.show()
